UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE CARTON IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT INSIDE WERE TWO OTHER CARTONS, THE LAST OF WHICH CONTAINED FOUR, LEAKING HALF PINT PLASTIC BOTTLES. THE ENTIRE CARTON AND CONTENTS WERE PLACED INTO A EIGHTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE HUB FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: THE CONSIGNEE DID NOT HAVE THE CONNECTIONS LABELED SO OUR DRIVER HAD THE UNLOADER SHOW HIM WHICH LINE HE WAS TO CONNECT THE PRODUCT LINE TO.  WHEN THIS TANK WAS COMPLETED THE OPERATOR SIGNED OUR WAYBILL CERTIFYING THAT THE PRODUCT HOSES WERE CONNECTED TO THE PROPER CONNECTION AND THAT THE RECEIVING VESSEL COULD HOLD THE CONTENTS OF THE CARGO TANK.  THE DRIVER THEN OPENED THE INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVES AND STARTED THE PUMP.  ALL INDICATIONS WERE THAT PRODUCT WAS BEING PUMPED OFF OF THE TRAILER ABOUT 45 MIN LATER THE DRIVER DETECTED THE PRODUCT HOSE WAS GETTING HOT TO THE TOUCH.  HE THEN TURNED OFF THE PUMP AT ABOUT THE SAME TIME THE HOSE BURST SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 1 1/2 GALLONS ON THE GROUND.  IT IS OUR BELIEF THAT THE CUSTOMERS LINE WAS BLOCKED IN SOME FASHION CAUSING IT TO OVER PRESSURIZE.

THE ITEM WAS BEING SORTED WHEN HANDLERS NOTICED A FORCED HISSING SOUND COMING FROM THE PACKAGE.  THE ITEM WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL A FIRE EXTINGUISHER UNIT. APPARENTLY THE RESTRAINING PIN HAD BECOME DISENGAGED FROM THE VALVE STEM. THIS ALLOWED THE UNIT TO INITIATE AND EXPEL ITS CONTENTS INTO THE OUTER PACKAGE.  THE UNIT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE RECIPIENT FOR DISPOSITION.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE ON INTERSTATE 35 NORTHBOUND IN DENTON, TEXAS, THE TRACTOR-TRAILER'S AIR-LINE RUPTURED, CAUSING THE BREAKS TO LOCK AND THE DRIVER TO PULL OVER TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD.  FREE PRODUCT WAS THEN DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY TEN GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND AFFECTED A SMALL AREA OF SOIL ALONGSIDE THE ROAD.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING, CAUSING THE BUNG TO BE STRIPPED FROM THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  THE DENTON FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO MONITOR THE SCENE.  HULCHER SERVICE, INC. OF DENTON, TEXAS RESPONDED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  HULCHER SERVICE, INC. PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, ABSORBENTS, AND SODA ASH TO NEUTRALIZE THE AREA.  ONE DRUM OF WASTE WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE HULCHER SERVICE, INC. FACILITY IN FORT WORTH, TEXAS FOR DISPOSAL COORDINATION.  THE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A NINETY-FIVE GALLON STEEL OVERPACK DRUM, WHICH WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  IT WILL BE HELD AT THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION AWAITING DISPOSITION.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: UPT DRIVER WAS NORTHBOUND ON US HWY-83, 6-MILES NORTH OF SUBLETTE, KS IN HASKELL CO. DRIVING A CLASS V VEHICLE LOADED WITH APPROX. 8500-GALLONS OF UNLEADED GASOLINE.  THIS ROAD IS POSTED 65-MPH AND OUR DRIVER WAS TRAVELING AT NO MORE THEN THE POSTED LIMIT.  A SECOND VEHICLE (DODGE P/U DUAL WHEEL) PULLING AN ALUMINUM CATTLE TRAILER ABOUT 35-FEET IN LENGTH FAILED TO STOP AS REQUIRED AT THE INTERSECTION AND ENTERED THE INTERSECTION AT ABOUT 40-MPH IN FRONT OF OUR UNIT.  OUR DRIVER HAD THE RIGHT OF WAY THROUGH THE INTERSECTION OF US HWY-83 @ KANSAS STATE HWY. 144.  THE P/U WAS TRAVELING THROUGH THE INTERSECTION FROM THE WEST TO THE EAST WHEN THE COLLISION OCCURRED.  OUR TRAILER WAS A 5-COMPARTMENT MC 406 ALUMINUM CARGO TANK.  THE NUMBER 1 AND NUMBER 5 COMPARTMENT FAILED AS A RESULT OF THE COLLISION AND IMPACT CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 3200 GALLONS OF GASOLINE SPILLAGE TO THE ENVIRONMENT ON THE ROW AND FARM LAND.  SITE WAS REMEDIATED TO ORIGINAL CONDITION UPON REMOVAL OF VEHICLES AND EQUIPMENT INVOLVED IN THE COLLISION.

column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: PLEASE REFER TO ATTACHMENT THAT WE SENT TO IDEM DATED 4/8/03: NATURE OF INCIDENT:  THE IBC WAS LOADED ON REAR OF TRAILER WITH AN ELECTRIC PALLET JACK STAGED UNDER THE IBC.  ACCORDING TO OUR DRIVER, THE IBC COULD NOT BE UNLOADED USING CALCHEM'S DOCK.  THEREFORE, THE TRAILER WAS PULLED AWAY FROM THE DOCK WITH THE INTENTION OF UNLOADING THE IBC WITH A FORKLIFT. THE ELECTRIC PALLET JACK HAD TO BE UNLOADED FIRST.  DUE TO LACK OF SPACE ON THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND LIMITED ROOM ON THE LIFT GATE, THE BRENNTAG DRIVER AND CALCHEM EMPLOYEE ELECTED TO USE FORKLIFT WITH PALLET AS AN ELEVATED PLATFORM FOR OUR DRIVER TO STAND ON AND THEN GUIDE THE ELECTRIC PALLET JACK FROM UNDER THE IBC ONTO THE LIFT GATE.  THE PALLET BROKE DURING THE PROCESS AND THE FORK OF THE ELECTRIC PALLET JACK GOT SHOVED INTO THE DISCHARGE VALVE ON THE IBC AND PULLED THE THREADED NIPPLE FROM THE VALVE BODY ON THE IBC.  THE MATERIAL GUSHED OUT AND GOT INSIDE OUR DRIVER'S BOOT. CALCHEM PERSONNEL TOOK OUR DRIVER TO ST. FRANCIS HOSPITAL.  OUR DRIVER WAS TREATED FOR 2ND DEGREE BURNS TO THE FEET DUE TO EXPOSURE TO THE AQUA AMMONIA.  INITIALLY, WE HAD ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1200 LBS OF AQUA AMMONIA SPILLED ON THE CUSTOMER'S GRAVEL DRIVE.  NO OTHER INJURIES WERE REPORTED.  CALCHEM PERSONNEL CONTAINED ABOUT HALF OF THE MATERIAL BY USING A ONE-WAY EMPTY PORTABLE TANK.

UPON DELIVERY, SEVEN BAGS WERE FOUND DAMAGED.  THE BAGS HAD SMALL HOLES IN THEM CAUSED  BY ANOTHER SKID, WHICH RUBBED AGAINST THEM IN TRANSIT.  THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE DAMAGED BAGS AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR.

PALLETS OF PAILS ARRIVED AT WILSONVILLE DOCK ON THE TAIL OF A TRAILER WITH PLYWOOD AROUND THREE SIDES.  ONE PAIL ON TOP OF THE CAN WAS DENTED AND STRONG CITRUS ODOR WAS PRESENT.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE FREIGHT SEVERAL PAILS HAD FLUID ON TOP OF THEM AND ONE PAIL HAD BEEN CRUSHED ON ONE SIDE. THERE WAS NO OTHER FREIGHT AROUND THE TOP OF THE PALLET AND WOULD PRESUMABLY HAVE BEEN DONE FROM POINT OF LOADING.  THE PAIL WAS SLOWLY LEAKING FROM UNDER A PLASTIC LABEL AND WOULD NOT CONTINUOUSLY LEAK UNTIL BOUNCING DOWN THE ROAD.  AT THE WILSONVILLE DOCK, WE HAD TO PEEL THE LABEL BACK IN ORDER TO FIND EXACTLY WHERE THE PAIL WAS LEAKING FROM.  THIS IS BELIEVED TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED DURING TRANSPORTATION IN THE CITY PICK-UP AND DELIVERY, AS THE DRIVER MAY HAVE TIED THE PALLET TO THE WALL AND DURING TRANSPORT THE LOAD SHIFTED CAUSING THE PAIL TO CRUSH.  BY USING PLYWOOD AS A BARRIER IN THE FUTURE THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT WILL BE AVOIDED.

TANK CAR, TJRX20465, LOAD ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING IN THE DEPARTURE YARD AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RICE TERMINAL IN WAYCROSS, GA.  A CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SENTINEL INSPECTED THE CAR AND ADVISED THE PROTECTIVE DOME LID WAS OPEN AND A 1/2 IN.  HOSE WAS HANGING OUT OF AN UNLOADING PORT.  CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THE HOSE WAS TAPED TO THE SAMPLE VALVE AND LIQUID PRODUCT WAS POURING OUT OF THE HOSE.  THE ENTIRE YARD WAS EVACUATED FOR APPROXIMATELY 3 HOURS AS A PRECAUTION.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  THEY USED A WATER FOG TO SUPPRESS VAPORS FROM THE TANK CAR.  STATE AND FEDERAL ENVIRONMENTAL AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SYSTEMS PERSONNEL RESPONDED.  THEY CLOSED THE SAMPLE VALVE, THE VALVE WAS OPEN 2 1/2 TURNS, AND RELEASE STOPPED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION INDICATED THAT AN OUTSIDE PARTY WAS ATTEMPTING TO STEAL PRODUCT FROM THE CAR.  IT IS SUSPECTED THAT WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED UNEXPECTEDLY THE HOSE BROKE, PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND THE PARTY FLED ON FOOT.  THE INVESTIGATION IS CONTINUING.  NARRI SCORE:490 5*(5+9+0)*(3+4)    CAUSE CODE:513

TRAIN, Q60206, WAS PULLING INTO CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN PENSACOLA, FL TO MAKE A SET OFF.  THE TRAIN PAST A SWITCH CREW WORKING ON AN ADJACENT TRACK.  THE ENGINEER AND THE CONDUCTOR ON THE SWITCHER REPORTED SMELLING A STRONG "SWEET" ODOR AND EXPERIENCED A  "PRICKLING" SENSATION ON THEIR FACE AND NECK.  THE CREW WAS BROUGHT INTO THE YARD OFFICE.  THE TRAINMASTER AND THE GENERAL FOREMAN WENT TO INVESTIGATE.  THEY WALKED BOTH SIDES OF THE TRACK WHERE THE TRAIN SET CARS OFF AND FOUND NO EVIDENCE OF ANY LEAKAGE NOR COULD THEY DETECT ANY UNUSUAL ODORS.  THE TRAINMASTER INSPECTED THE CARS IN Q60206 AS IT DEPARTED THE YARD AND SAW NO INDICATION OF ANY LEAKAGE OR ANY ODOR.  THE SWITCH CREW REPORTED THEY FELT BETTER AFTER HAVING COME INSIDE FOR A LITTLE WHILE BUT THEY REQUESTED TO GO HOME TO TAKE A SHOWER AND CHANGE CLOTHES.  ON 04-08, CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER RESPONDED TO CONTINUE THE INVESTIGATION.  HE INSPECTED THE VALVES, FITTINGS AND CLOSURES OF ALL THE TANK CARS THAT WERE SET OFF BY Q60206 THE PREVIOUS DAY.  HE DISCOVERED PRODUCT VAPORS COMING FROM THE MANWAY COVER OF GATX16992 A LOAD CORROSIVE LIQUID, NOS.  HE FOUND THAT 4 OF THE 6 MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE LOOSE.  THREE WERE LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT AND ONE WAS LESS THAN HAND TIGHT.  HE MADE ALL THE MANWAY BOLT WRENCH TIGHT. THE VAPOR RELEASE STOPPED AND THE ODOR SUBSIDED.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF A LIQUID RELEASE ALTHOUGH IT WAS RAINING AT THE TIME.  THE SHIPPER, MERICHEM, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC AND ADVISED OF THE RR EMPLOYEE EXPOSURES.  MERICHEM EXPLAINED THAT KINDER MORGAN TERMINAL LOADED THE CAR AND THAT THEY WOULD CONTACT KINDER MORGAN AND REQUEST THEY CONDUCT A FORMAL INVESTIGATION.  IN THE MEANTIME, ALL THREE MEMBERS OF THE SWITCH CREW RETURNED TO WORK ON 04-08.  THEY ALL INDICATED THAT THEY FELT BETTER AND DECLINED ANY MEDICAL ASSISTANCE.  NARRI SCORE:100    5*(5+5+0)*(2+0) CAUSE CODE: 200

UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT DEPARTMENT, THE DRUM WAS REMOVED FROM THE SHIPMENT AND SECURED FOR TRANSIT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.

WHILE AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY, ONE DRUM WAS FOUND LEAKING ON THE DOCK. THE DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM A HOLE CAUSED BY A FORKLIFT.  UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT DEPARTMENT, THE DRUM WAS REMOVED FROM THE SHIPMENT AND SECURED FOR TRANSIT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.

UPON OFF LOADING AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY, ONE DRUM WAS FOUND LEAKING. THE DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM A BUNG CAP, WHICH WAS CRUSHED DOWN INTO THE PRODUCT IN THE DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK, ALONG WITH THE SPILL CLEAN UP PAD, AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

WHILE IN TRANSIT, THE DRIVER NOTICED SOMETHING LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER. THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT DEPARTMENT DISPATCHED A SPILL CONTRACTOR TO THE SCENE TO HANDLE THIS SPILL.  THE SPILL CONTRACTOR FOUND A DRUM LEAKING FROM A HOLE CAUSED BY A FORK BLADE.  THE SPILL CONTRACTOR OVER PACKED THE DAMAGED DRUM FOR SAFE TRANSIT AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT OUTSIDE THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED UP ALSO.

UPON DELIVERY, ONE CARTON WAS FOUND DAMAGED AND LEAKING.  THE CARTON WAS DAMAGED WHEN ANOTHER SKID OF FREIGHT WAS JAMMED INTO THE SIDE OF THE SKID AT THE TIME OF LOADING.  THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT.

UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DELANCO FACILITY IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT TOP STACKED FREIGHT STACKED ON OTHER DRUMS HAD PUNCTURED THE VALVE ON THE BOTTOM DRUM. ONE HALF GALLON OF LIQUID WAS SPILLED ON TOP OF THE DRUM.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND PACKED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE DAMAGED CONTAINER WAS OVER PACKED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SPILL MATERIAL WILL BE HELD IN THE HAZARDOUS WASTE STORAGE AREA AREA PENDING DISPOSAL BY AN OUTSIDE VENDOR.

DRIVER WAS FILLING EQUIPMENT OF DIESEL FUEL PRIOR TO A SIMULATION JOB. WHILE THE TRUCK PUMP WAS ENGAGED THE 2 INCH HOSE FROM THE DISCHARGE SIDE OF THE PUMP TO THE METER CAME OFF THE PUMP CONNECTION.  AT THIS POINT, EVERYTHING WAS SHUT DOWN.  APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS SPILLED ON THE GROUND.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: THE DRIVER'S DESCRIPTION OF THE INITIAL EVENT:  "DID NOT PUT HOSE ON DOWNSPOUT AND START FLOW.  SPILL DIESEL ON GROUND OUT OF OPEN HOSE.  OPEN INTERNAL AND BUTTERFLY WITHOUT PUT HOSE ON DOWNSPOUT."  THIS RESULTED IN A SPILL THAT WAS ESTIMATED BY THE DRIVER TO BE LESS THAN 10 GALLONS.  THE INITIAL RESPONSE BY THE DRIVER WAS TO ATTEMPT TO CONTROL THE MATERIAL BY USING THE ABSORBENT MATERIALS AVAILABLE TO HIM (ABSORBENT PADS AND "KITTY LITTER").  UPON NOTIFICATION OF THE INCIDENT DISPATCH PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED OUR COMPANY RESPONSE PEOPLE AND DISPATCHED THEM TO THE SCENE. LOCAL POLICE AND FIRE RESPONDED AS WELL.  ONCE THE FIRE INSPECTOR ASSESSED THE SITUATION AND INFORMED US THAT THERE WAS MORE MATERIAL SPILLED THAN INITIALLY BELIEVED AND THAT THE CLEAN UP WAS GOING TO BE BEYOND THE EQUIPMENT CAPABILITIES OF OUR RESPONSE PERSONNEL WE CALLED ECOLOGY CONTROL INDUSTRIES (AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY) TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE WITH A VACUUM TRUCK, HIGH PRESSURE HOT WATER WASHER AND CREW.  ABOUT AN HOUR LATER E.C.I CALLED BACK WITH THE NEWS THAT THEY WOULD NOT BE ABLE TO RESPOND AS THEIR EQUIPMENT WAS NOT AVAILABLE AND SUGGESTED THAT WE CALL FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL.  WE AGREED AND DID IN FACT CALL FOSS WHO RESPONDED WITHIN THE HOUR WITH ALL EQUIPMENT AND CREW TO COMPLETE THE CLEANUP.  WHILE ALL OF THIS WAS HAPPENING OUR RESPONSE PEOPLE HAD DEPLOYED MORE ABSORBENT MATERIALS (ABSORBENT PADS, "KITTY LITTER" AND 3 10 FT. SECTIONS OF ABSORBENT BOOM) TO FURTHER CONTROL AND ABSORB ANY DIESEL THAT MAY HAVE MADE ITS WAY TO THE GUTTER.  UPON THE ARRIVAL OF THE FOSS CREW AND EQUIPMENT THE FIRE INSPECTOR REVIEWED HIS REQUIREMENTS FOR THE CLEANUP WITH US AND TURNED THE SCENE OVER TO US AND OUR CONTRACTOR TO COMPLETE.  THE AREA SPECIFIED WAS WASHED DOWN, ALL WASH WATER WAS COLLECTED, CATCH BASINS VACUUMED AND ALL RESULTING WASTE REMANDED TO FOSS FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  FINAL INQUIRIES CONCLUDED THAT 40 GALLONS OF DIESEL HAD BEEN SPILLED AND CLEANED UP.

THE DRIVER HAD HOOKED UP THE OFF-LOADING LINE AND WAS STARTING TO OFF-LOAD THE PRODUCT WHEN IT STARTED TO BACK-UP IN THE CUSTOMER UNLOADING LINE.  THE UNLOADING LINE WAS PLUGGED AND THE CUSTOMER HAD TO UNPLUG THE LINE.  AFTER THE CUSTOMER UNPLUGGED THE LINE THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO FINISH UNLOADING WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  THE PRODUCT WAS ALL CONTAINED IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA AROUND THE UNLOADING AREA.  THE CUSTOMER TOOK FULL RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE CLEAN-UP.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: THE DRIVER HAD FINISHED UNLOADING AND HAD BLED THE PRESSURE OUT OF THE UNLOADING LINES PRIOR TO DISCONNECTING.  WHEN THE DRIVER DISCONNECTED FROM THE CUSTOMERS CONNECTION PRESSURE HAD BUILT-UP IN THE LINE CAUSING PRODUCT TO SPRAY OUT AS A MIST.  DRIVER SHOULD HAVE LEFT THE BLEEDER VALVE IN THE OPEN POSITION PRIOR TO DISCONNECTING.  THE DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTED TO LSU MEDICAL IN SHREVEPORT, LA.  THE DRIVER WAS TREATED AND KEPT OVERNIGHT FOR OBSERVATION AND RELEASED THE NEXT DAY.  THE SPRAYED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED-UP BY ARCH CHEMICAL NO MEASURABLE AMOUNT.  THE DRIVER WAS PLACED WITH A DRIVER TRAINER TO BE EVALUATED AND RE-TRAINED ON PROPER PROCEDURES.
THE RELEASE WAS CAUSED BY DRIVER ERROR.  THE DRIVER FAILED TO SECURE THE DOME LUGS.  HAD SLIGHT LEAK FROM DOME.  OIL DRY WAS SPREAD AND MIDWEST ENVIRONMENTAL DID THE CLEAN-UP.

THE DRIVER HAD 2 DIFFERENT PRODUCTS ON.  AFTER UNLOADING THE BONDRITE CONSIGNEE CLOSED THE VALVE ON THE STORAGE TANK.  THE DRIVER UNHOOKED THE TRANSFER HOSE FROM THE TRAILER WENT INSIDE OF THE BUILDING AND STARTED TO UNHOOK THE HOSE FROM THE STORAGE TANK AND HOSE WAS HEAVY WITH PRODUCT.  HE CALLED FOR THE UNLOADING SUPERVISOR AND IT WAS DETERMINED THE SUPERVISOR CLOSED THE WRONG VALVE.  ALL PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND FLOOR DRY SPREAD AND SHOP-VAC ALL PRODUCT INTO 30 GALLON DRUM.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: PET UNIT HAULING 7600 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL (FUEL OIL) ROLLED UNIT WHILE ATTEMPTING A LEFT TURN UNDER AN OVERPASS.  TANK CAME TO REST ON A CONCRETE CURB CAUSING TANK SHELL TO FAIL.  DRIVER WAS TICKETED FOR FAILURE TO CONTROL SPEED.  HE WENT INTO THE TURN AT TOO HIGH A RATE OF SPEED. TRAINING WILL REINFORCE NEED TO STAY FOCUSED AND REEXPLAIN PRODUCT MOVEMENT IN CARGO TANKS WITH HIGH CENTERS OF GRAVITY.

ACCORDING TO OUR DRIVER, HE THOUGHT HE HAD THE LOADING NOZZLE INSERTED FULLY IN THE TANKER AND WHEN HE STARTED THE LOADING PROCESS, THE #6 OIL SPILLED ON THE CATWALK AND THEN RAN DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TANKER AND ONTO THE GROUND.  I SPOKE TO CHERYL JACKSON AT SUN AND SHE INFORMED ME THAT SUN WILL BEGIN THE CLEANUP PROCESS AND REPORT THE SPILL TO THE PROPER AUTHORITIES.  OUR DRIVER HAS BEEN VERBALLY INFORMED THAT SAFETY MEASURES ARE IN PLACE FOR THE PROTECTION OF NOT ONLY HIM, BUT FOR THE ENVIRONMENT AND TOLD HIM TO BE MORE ALERT WHEN LOADING AND UNLOADING PETROLEUM PRODUCTS.

THIS PACKAGE WAS PACKED WITH (2) 1 GALLON BUCKETS LAYING ON THEIR SIDE. THERE WAS AIR BAGS IN THE BOX, BUT THIS WOULD NOT HELP OR PREVENT THE BOTTLES FROM LEAKING.  AS THE PACKAGE WAS ACROSS THE BELT (FROM ONE TO THE OTHER), THE CAP POPPED OFF CAUSING ONE OF THE TWO BOTTLES TO LEAK COMPLETELY OUT.  WHEN THE LIQUID HIT THE METAL, IT HAD A CHEMICAL REACTION. AFTER THE SPILLED CONTENTS WERE CONTAINED AND MOVED TO THE PSC AREA, THE BAG HEATED UP AND STARTED TO SMOKE.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN IN THE FUTURE, THE BOTTLES SHOULD BE PLACED UPRIGHT AND BE PROPERLY LABELED, INCLUDING ORIENTATION LABELS.  ALL PROCESSED THRU DMP. CLEANED AND STORED EQUIPMENT.

RESPONDER CALLED TO LEAKING PACKAGE.  DONNED FULL PPE, SECURED AREA, APPLIED DECISION TREE, IDENTIFIED CONTENTS AND MOVED TO A MORE SECURE AREA. DESIGNATED RESPONDER:  JOE WEBBER

THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND AFFECTED DUNNAGE WERE PLACED INTO TWO, FIFTY FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUMS, AND ONE THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A SIXTY FIVE GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM. ALL FOUR DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE DAMAGE OF THE BAG WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY ADJACENT FREIGHT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, WHISK BROOM, AND DUST PAN. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE DAMAGED BAG WAS PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  BOTH DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

APPROXIMATELY EIGHT OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND ABSORBENTS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT MATERIALS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS  WERE PLACED INTO ONE,  FIVE GALLON FIBER AND ONE, FIFTY FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, BOTH DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE LEAKING BUNG ON THEN DRUM WAS SEALED AND IT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE,  FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.   APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING A NEUTRALIZER. THE BUNG WAS TIGHTENED ON THE DRUM, AND IT WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING, FIFTY- FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALF MARK OF THE TRAILER.   APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO IMPROPER BLOCKING, CAUSING THE DRUM TO FALL OVER DURING TRANSIT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING TYVEK SUITS, GLOVES, DUST MASK, AMPHOMAG  AND ABSORBENT PADS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS CLEANED, RECOUPED AND  FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON, CONTAINING FOUR,  ONE GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLES WAS DISCOVERED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE BOTTLE WAS DAMAGED AND THE REMAINING THREE BOTTLES WERE AFFECTED.   APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE DAMAGE TO THE BOTTLE WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY THE OTHER FREIGHT DURING LOADING.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, GOGGLES, AMPHOMAG, AND ABSORBENTS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WET CARTON AND DAMAGED BOTTLES WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM,  WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE THREE AFFECTED BOTTLES WERE CLEANED, RECOUPED AND FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM CONTACTED INLAND WATERS OF CLEVELAND, OHIO TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  THEY PERFORMED THE CLEANUP AND PLACED THE LEAKING ONE HUNDRED AND TEN GALLON PLASTIC DRUM INTO AN OVER PACK DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: LINE DRIVER CURT LUND HAD A TRAILER THAT WAS LEAKING FLUID FROM THE REAR END.  WE CHECKED THE HM PAPERWORK AND FOUND OUT IT WAS FLAMMABLE LIQUID. WE OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR AND FOUND THE LEAKING FREIGHT.  WE BACK STRIPPED THE TRAILER UNTIL WE GOT TO THE FREIGHT.  WHEN FREIGHT WAS ON THE DOCK WE REMOVED THE LEAKING DRUMS (OR PAILS).  RECOUPED THE PALLET THEN RELOADED THE TRAILER. AFTER ALL CLEAN UP WAS DONE.  THE PAILS WERE LEAKING FROM THE TOP WELD AND THE BOTTOM.  THE DAMAGE LOOKS LIKE IT WAS CAUSED BY A FORKLIFT.  WE SENT SPILL REPORT AND GAVE FEED BACK TO THE ORIGIN SERVICE CENTER FOR FOLLOW UP.

EMPLOYEE WAS TAKEN TO NEARBY HOSPITAL, EXAMINED FOR CHEMICAL EXPOSURE TO FACIAL SKIN AND RELEASED WITHOUT FURTHER TREATMENT. BNSF  AND CONTRACT RESPONDERS FOUND THE 2 INCH LIQUID EDUCTION PIPE CAP NOT APPLIED AND RESPONDERS SECURED IT IN PLACE.  CONTRACTOR NEUTRALIZED AND WIPED SPILLED ACID THAT IMPACTED TANK CAR SHELL.

CDT, 4/12/  AFTERWARDS, NO FURTHER AMMONIA ODOR DETECTED AND YARD OPERATIONS RESUMED.

column168: BNSF ROAD SWITCHER PERFORMING SWITCHING IN RAIL YARD DERAILED SIX TANK CARS WITH TWO OF THESE ON THEIR SIDES AFTER CARS ENCOUNTERED A SWITCH POINT DERAIL.  THESE SIX RAIL CARS ALONG WITH OTHERS ROLLED AWAY FROM A STOPPED SWITCH CUT THAT HAD JUST BEEN SHOVED TO REST.  A PREVIOUS COUPLING EVENT FAILED TO PROPERLY COUPLE ALL RAIL CARS AND THE CREW FAILED TO ENSURE ALL RAIL CARS WERE PROPERLY COUPLED. column168: ON MONDAY APRIL 28TH AT 07:15PM WHILE MAKING A DELIVERY IN CENTERVILLE,MA AN XOM DRIVER SPILLED APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF SUPER UNLEADED GASOLINE. THE UNLOADING VALVE FOR THE 2000-GALLON COMPARTMENT APPEARED TO BEING THE CLOSED POSITION WHEN THE DRIVER PULLED THE DUST CAP OFF. THERE WAS A MECHANICAL FAILURE WITH THE Y-VALVE. THE PACKING NUT ON THE Y-VALVE FOR THE #2 COMPARTMENT WAS CORREDED CAUSING THE VALVE TO GET STUCK IN THE OPEN POSITION EVEN THROUGH THE HANDLE APPEARED TO BE IN THE CLOSED POSITION. THIS WAS VERIFIED UNDER THE LOADING RACK THE NEXT DAY THE EAST PROVIDENCE MECHANICS HAD TO GET THE PRODUCT PUMPED OFF THE TRUCK. WHEN THE DUST CAP WAS REMOVED THE GAS GUSHED OUT OF THE #2 COMPARTMENT OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER HAD THE NUMBER 4 COMPARTMENT UNLOADING WHEN THE SPILL OCCURRED. THE CENTERVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED, THE EAST PROVIDENCE CONTINGENCY PLAN WAS ACTIVATED, AND THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP. NO PRODUCT REACHED ANY STORM DRAINS. CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE DISPOSED OF PROPERLY BY CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL.

column168: CSX TRANSPORTATION (CSXT) RECEIVED A REPORT THAT TANK CAR, TEIX 30107, LOAD PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, NOS, WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING ON THE INTERCHANGE TRACK BETWEEN CSXT AND THE NORFOLK SOUTHERN (NS).  CSXT'S TRAINMASTER RESPONDED.  THE NS CONDUCTOR REPORTED THE CAR LEAKING FROM THE TOP WHEN HE WAS SWITCHING THE TRACK.  HE REPORTED THE LEAK TO HIS TRAINMASTER WHO NOTIFIED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE CONSIGNEE, REGIONAL ENTERPRISES. REGIONAL ENTERPRISES RESPONDED.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS GONE WHEN THEY ARRIVED.  THE CAR WAS LEAKING CONTINUOUSLY FROM THE TOP WHEN THEY ARRIVED. THE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING AROUND THE BASE OF THE LIQUID EDUCTION PIPE WHERE IT IS THREADED INTO THE PLATE.  THEY TIGHTENED THE PIPE 4-5 TURNS TO MAKE IT WRENCH TIGHT.  THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE LIQUID VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE VALVE PLUG WAS WRENCH TIGHT.  ABSORBENT PADS WERE STUFFED AROUND THE PIPES AND THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING WAS CLOSED AND SECURED.  REGIONAL ENTERPRISE ESTIMATED 3-5 GALLONS SPILLED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC AND REGIONAL ENTERPRISE TALKED TO THEM ABOUT PROBLEM FOUND WITH THE CAR.  THE CAR DELIVERED TO REGIONAL ENTERPRISES WITHOUT FURTHER PROBLEM.  NARRI SCORE:  80.  5* (5+3+0) * (2+0).  CAUSE CODE:  282

column168: ON TUESDAY NIGHT AT ABOUT 1700 HOURS, OUR DRIVER DONNIE VANOVER WAS HEADING EAST ON I-84 IN THE AREA OF DANBURY, CT.  WHEN SUDDENLY A VEHICLE STOPPED IN FRONT OF HIM AND HE REAR ENDED INTO THE REAR OF THE VEHICLE. WE WERE PULLING A LOAD OF HAZARDOUS WASTE MATERIAL FROM CLEAN HARBORS IN CINCINNATI, OHIO TO THEIR FACILITY IN BRISTOL, CT; ON THE TRAILER WERE DRUMS OF WASTE SODIUM CYANIDE SOLUTION.  ON THE TRAILER IN FRONT OF THE DRUMS OF CYANIDE SOLUTIONS WAS A PALLET OF MISC., A/C COMPRESSOR PARTS. THE DRUMS STAND ABOUT 4 FEET HIGH AND THE PALLET OF PARTS WAS ONLY 1.5 FEET HIGH.  DUE TO THE WAY THE LOAD WAS LOADED THE DRUMS SHIFTED AND ONE OF THEM WAS OPENED ON THE BOTTOM, WHEN IT FLIPPED OVER THE PALLET OF A/C PARTS. THERE MUST HAVE BEEN A COUPLE OF RODS STICKING OUT FROM THE PALLET AS THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM IN QUESTIONS HAVE TWO SLASH HOLES IN IT. THIS WAS FIBER DRUM. (SEE PICTURES ENCLOSED).  THE CLEAN UP WAS PERFORMED BY FLEET ENVIRONMENTAL, OF BETHAL, CT. AT THIS TIME OF FILING THIS REPORT WE HAVE NOT RECEIVED THE FINAL REPORT FROM FLEET ENVIRONMENTAL, AS SOON AS THIS IS DONE I WILL FORWARD THEM ON TO YOUR OFFICE, SO THAT YOU CAN ATTACH TO THE FILE.  IF YOU HAVE NAY QUESTIONS ON THIS MEMO, PLEASE CALL ME AT 1-732-424-8441 EXT 106.

column168: DRIVER LOADED LOAD 4/22/03 NORMALLY.  DROVE FROM SUFFOLK VA TO SALISBURY NC WHERE HE SPENT THE NIGHT.  DURING PRE-TRIP INSPECTION SAW PRODUCT LEAKING THROUGH TRAILER TO GROUND.  IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED LOCAL AUTHORITIES, SHIPPER, AND CALLED CHEMTREC FOR INSTRUCTIONS.BLOCKED OFF PORTION OF TRUCK STOP TO PREVENT OTHER VEHICLES FROM SPREADING SPILL.  SHIPPER PROVIDED CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR WHO TOOK OVER FOR LOCAL AUTHORITIES. CAUSE OF SPILL WAS BARRELS HAD SHIFTED SLIGHTLY DURING TRANSIT, CAUSING A PROTRUDING NAIL TO PUNCTURE THE BOTTOM OF A 1H1 DRUM.  USE OF BETTER QUALITY PALLETS OF PADDING BETWEEN PALLETS AND DRUM WOULD HAVE PREVENTED SPILL.  ALSO, BETTER SECUREMENT OF THE DRUMS TO THE PALLETS WOULD HAVE PREVENTED MOVEMENT OF THE DRUM OVER THE PROTRUDING NAIL.

DURING AN UNLOADING OPERATION AT THE AMERICAN SKI COMPANY CANYONS RESORT IN PARK CITY, UTAH, 327 GALLONS OF AN ON/OFF ROAD DIESEL FUEL MIXTURE WAS RELEASED.  THE RECEIVING TANK WAS NOT PLUMBED WITH A SEPARATE FILL LINE, REQUIRING THE DRIVER TO REMOVE THE 90% OVERFLOW FITTING TO ALLOW FILLING THE TANK.  ACCORDING TO THE DRIVER THE TANK OVERFLOW ALARM WAS ALSO NOT FUNCTIONING.  DURING THE LOADING OF THE STORAGE TANK, THE DRIVER NOTED FUEL FLOWING OUT THE FILL HOLE.  THE FUEL RAN ACROSS A HARD PACKED DIRT OVER FLOW PARKING LOT, DOWN A SLOPE AND INTO A LOCAL STORM DRAIN, NOT CONNECTED TO ANY STORM SEWER SYSTEM OUTSIDE THE RESORT.  THE STORM SEWER EMPTIED INTO A RETENTION POND, WITH AN OVERFLOW TO A STREAM. NO FUEL LEFT THE RETENTION POND.  THERE WAS ALSO STANDING FUEL ON THE PARKING LOT AND AROUND THE STORAGE TANK.  A TOTAL OF 327 GALLONS WAS DETERMINED TO HAVE BEEN RELEASED. ACTION TAKEN AT THE TIME OF DISCOVERY: THE DRIVER STOPPED DISPENSING FUEL IMMEDIATELY UPON DISCOVERING THE OVERFLOW.  HE EVENTUALLY MADE CONTACT WITH PERSONNEL AT THE CANYONS RESORT TO LET THEM KNOW WHAT HAD HAPPENED, CONTACTED HIS DISPATCH WHO CONTACTED TW COMPANY TO ASSIST IN THE CLEAN UP.  IN THE MEAN TIME, THE PARK CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT, UTAH HIGHWAY PATROL (UHP) HAZMAT DIVISION, AND SUMMIT COUNTY HEALTH DEPARTMENT HAD BEEN CALLED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT PLACED ABSORBENT PADS ON THE FUEL ON THE GROUND, MONITORED THE SEWER LINES FOR PRESENCE OF LEL AND SECURED THE AREA WITH ASSISTANCE FROM THE UHP.  THE RESORT PERSONNEL USED A TRASH PUMP TO BEGIN RECOVERING FUEL FROM THE GROUND AROUND THE TANK.  THE CANYONS, AND JARDINE PETROLEUM MADE NOTIFICATIONS TO NRC THE STATE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, THE SERC AND THE LEPC.  TW COMPANY PLACED BOTH ABSORBENT AND CONTAINMENT BOOM IN THE RETENTION POND, MOVED THE FUEL TO A CONVENIENT LOCATION AND REMOVED IT USING A VACUUM TRUCK.  BOOMS WERE LEFT IN THE RETENTION POND WHILE REMOVAL OF THE FREE LIQUIDS OCCURRED UP GRADIENT AND DURING THE EXCAVATION OF THE CONTAMINATED SOILS.  ALL CONTAMINATED SOILS WERE EXCAVATED AND DISPOSED OF AS NON-REGULATED WASTE, SOLID NOS, ALONG WITH THE ABSORBENT BOOMS AND PADS, FOLLOWING LABORATORY ANALYSIS.  THE RECOVERED FUEL/WATER WAS DISPOSED OF AS A NON HAZARDOUS LIQUID ALSO FOLLOWING LABORATORY ANALYSIS.  TW COMPANY TOOK WATER SAMPLES DURING AND AFTER THE CLEANUP TO INSURE THAT NOT FUEL LEFT THE RETENTION POND AND THAT THE CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETE AND SUCCESSFUL.  DURING AD AFTER THE REMOVAL OF CONTAMINATED SOILS DIRECT READING WERE TAKEN USING A PHOTO IONIZATION DETECTOR (PID) TO CONFIRM LOCATION OF AND ADEQUATE REMOVAL OF THE CONTAMINATED SOILS.  RUN OFF DURING THE CLEAN UP ACTIVITIES WAS CONTROLLED WITH STRAW BAILS TO KEEP SEDIMENT FROM REACHING THE STORM SEWER. ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS: THE DRIVER WAS INTERVIEWED, AND PROCEDURES FOR LOADING FUEL AT THIS LOCATION WERE REVIEWED.  JARDINE IS WORKING WITH THE CANYONS RESORT TO REMEDY THE PROBLEM.  ALL JARDINE DR

LOADER WAS ATTEMPTING TO PICK UP PALLET, FORKS HAD NOT BEEN LOWERED PREVIOUSLY AND HE PUNCTURED PRODUCT UPON CONTACT.  WE SECURED SPILL AND PROCEEDED TO CLEAN UP AREA.  FORKLIFT OPERATION WAS COUNSELLED ABOUT PROPER PROCEDURES OF OPERATION.
WHEN WE STARTED UNLOADING THE TRAILER AND GOT TO THE SKID IT WAS ALREADY LEAKING.

THIS INCIDENT WAS A RESULT OF PACKAGING FAILURE.  THERE WAS A PIN SIZED HOLE IN THE GALLON JUG INSIDE OF A BOX.  NO HOLES WERE FOUND IN THE BOX SURROUNDING THE JUGS.  THE CONTAINER THEREFORE LEAKED ALL THE WAY IN TRANSIT FROM DANVILLE, IL TO CINCINNATI, OH.  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED ON PACKAGING FAILURE.

column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS PARKED IN THE NEVADA LANDING CASINO PARKING LOT WHEN A CASINO SECURITY PERSON OBSERVED MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF CARGO TANK.  PERSON MADE 9-1-1 CALL TO REPORT. SPILL WAS CONFINED TO A SMALL AREA IMMEDIATELY UNDER THE REAR OF TRAILER.  FOUR-BOLT BLIND FLANGE AT CARGO TANK DISCHARGE LINE WAS NOT SECURED TIGHT ENOUGH, HOWEVER, LEAKING HAD STOPPED WITHOUT INTERVENTION.  FOUR BOLTS ON FLANGE WERE TIGHTENED.  H20 ENVIRONMENTAL APPLIED SODA ASH TO SPILL FOR NEUTRALIZATION AND RECOVERED LESS THAN 2 GALLONS OF NEUTRALIZED MATERIAL.  SUBSEQUENT INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVE LEAKED, WHICH ALLOWED PRODUCT TO ACCUMULATE IN HEADER.  BLIND FLANGE WAS NOT SECURE ENOUGH TO PREVENT LEAK.  TRAILER WAS ALMOST DUE FOR ANNUAL HM INSPECTIONS.  TRAILER TAKEN OUT-OF-SERVICE FOR REPAIRS AND REQUIRED HM INSPECTIONS.  REVIEW OF INSPECTIONS AND MAINTENANCE PROCEDURES IS CURRENTLY UNDERWAY TO DETERMINE IF MODIFICATIONS ARE NEEDED TO PREVENT A RE-OCCURRENCE OF THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT.

column168: ON APRIL 22, 2003, ACTION ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO AN OVERTURNED BOREN EXPLOSIVE TRUCK ON THE I-59 ON RAMP TO I-459, BESSEMER, ALABAMA.  AMFO AND EMULSION WERE RELEASED ONTO THE SOIL ON THE SHOULDER OF THE INTERSTATE. THE RELEASED PRODUCT AND IMPACTED SOIL WERE LOADED INTO TWO (2) ROLL OFF BOXES WITH A RUBBER TIRED BACKHOE AND BOBCAT.  THE ROLL OFF BOXES WERE RETURNED TO ACTION'S SECURE FACILITY IN HANCEVILLE, ALABAMA FOR STORAGE PENDING DISPOSAL AUTHORIZATION.  INITIALLY, MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEETS WERE PROVIDED TO WASTE MANAGEMENT, INC. TO DETERMINE IF THE WASTE COULD BE MANAGE AT EITHER A SUBTITLE C OR SUBTITLE D LANDFILL.  BASED ON THEIR REVIEW OF THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEETS, WASTE MANAGEMENT DETERMINED THAT THE MATERIAL COULD NOT BE MANAGED BY LANDFILLING.  MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEETS WERE THEN PROVIDED TO ONYX ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES FOR THEIR REVIEW. BASED ON ONYX'S REVIEW, IT APPEARS THAT THE WASTE CAN BE MANAGED BY INCINERATION AT PORT ARTHUR, TEXAS OR SAUGET, ILLINOIS.  WE ANTICIPATE THAT DISPOSAL AUTHORIZATION WILL BE RECEIVED WITHIN SEVEN TO TEN DAYS. FOLLOWING RECEIPT OF DISPOSAL AUTHORIZATION,  THE ROLL OFF BOXES WILL BE TRANSPORTED TO ONYX FOR PROPER MANAGEMENT.  MANIFEST AND WEIGHT TICKETS, DOCUMENTING PROPER DISPOSAL, WILL BE FORWARDED TO YOU AT THE COMPLETION OF THE PROJECT.

OTHER TWO CONTAINERS WERE RELOADED TO VESSEL.  RESPONSE TEAM CLIFF BERRY WAS CALLED IN TO HANDLE CLEAN UP OPERATIONS.  PRODUCT ON VESSEL DECK WAS CLEANED WITH ABSORBENT. column168: WHILE ENROUTE TRANSPORT UNIT OVERTURNED WHILE NEGOTIATING A TURN.  CONTACT W/ROADWAY TORE A HOLE IN THE TANK CAUSING RELEASE OF APPROX. 6000 GALLONS OF JET FUEL.  FUEL CONTAMINATED THE SOIL AT A NEARBY PARK AND EVENTUALLY MADE ITS WAY INTO THE WATERWAY.  THE BAY WAS BOOMED TO PRECLUDE FURTHER CONTAMINATION.  AREA WAS FOAMED BY LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT.  TRANSPORT WAS RIGHTED AND REMOVED FROM THE SCENE, AND CLEAN UP WAS BEGUN IMMEDIATELY. APPROX 95 TONS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED BY CLEAN HARBORS.  CONTAINED FUEL WAS COLLECTED AND DISPOSED OF.  BOOMS WERE LEFT IN THE BAY FOR SEVERAL DAYS.  ONE MALLARD DUCK WAS CONTAMINATED BY FUEL.

column168: OUR TRUCK & TANKER TRAILER - CAME UPON SLOWED TRAFFIC - COULD NOT STOP - BEFORE REAR ENDING TANKER IN FRONT OF HIM - CHOSE TO LEAVE THE ROAD INSTEAD - TRUCK & LOADED TRAILER LAID OVER.  LEAKAGE SEEMED TO OCCUR AT THE DOME LIDS & VENTS AS PRESSURE OF WEIGHT AND POSITION OF TANKER.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE.  DEQ & OUR EMPLOYEES WERE AT THE SCENE AS QUICKLY AS POSSIBLE. TANKER WAS UNLOADED INTO ANOTHER ONE OF OUR TANKERS AT SITE.  WRECKER PULLED TRUCK & TANKER FROM SITE WHEN RELEASED BY EMERGENCY RESPONSE. DRIVER WAS TAKEN FOR DRUG & ALCOHOL POST ACCIDENT EXAM IMMEDIATELY - REPORTS WERE OK LATER.  DRIVER WENT TO ER AT HOSPITAL.  X-RAYED AND RELEASED. NO SERIOUS INJURIES - WE WERE THANKFUL THAT ALL OUR LOSSES WERE REPLACEABLE.  I DID REPORT A WRITTEN LETTER TO OUR STATE - MDEQ - WHICH I AM ENCLOSING A COPY OF IT TO YOU - I REGRET I FAILED TO DO THIS PROPERLY.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 18, 2003, OLIN CORP ADVISED CSX TRANSPORTATION OF A CONDITION REPORTED TO THEM BY THEIR CUSTOMER, E I DUPONT OF AMPTHILL, VA.  OVER THE COURSE OF THE PAST YEAR AND ONE HALF, DUPONT HAS DISCOVERED SMALL AMOUNTS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE RESIDUE AROUND THE BASE OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) ON 39 TANK CARS AFTER THEY HAD BEEN UNLOADED AT THE AMPTHILL, VA FACILITY.  ALL OF THE CARS ARE EQUIPPED WITH MIDLAND EXTERNAL PRD AND THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE TO INDICATE THE RESIDUE PRESENT WAS THE RESULT OF A PRODUCT RELEASE DURING TRANSPORTATION.  OLIN INSPECTED AND TESTED SEVERAL OF THE PRD'S AND FOUND NO MECHANICAL PROBLEMS OR DEFECTS WITH THEM.  OLIN REQUESTED CSXT'S ASSISTANCE TO REVIEW THE ROUTING AND HANDLING OF THEIR TANK CARS TRANSPORTED TO DUPONT'S  AMPTHILL, VA PLANT.  THE ROUTING INDICATED THE CARS SHIPPED FROM OLIN'S NIAGARA FALLS, NY PLANT WERE SWITCHED AT CSXT'S RAIL YARDS IN NIAGARA FALLS, NY, SELKIRK, NY, RICHMOND, VA, AND BELLWOOD, VA FOR DELIVERY TO DUPONT AT AMPTHILL.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE FROM CSXT, DUPONT OR OLIN THAT ANY OF THE CARS IN QUESTION HAD EXPERIENCED ANY UNUSUAL HANDLING OR HARD COUPLING'S IN TRANSIT.  CSXT WITH OLIN'S CORPORATION HAD INITIATED A PLAN TO EQUIP SEVERAL TANK CARS WITH IMPACT RECORDERS THAT WILL MONITOR COUPLING IMPACTS TO DETERMINE IF CAR HANDLING COULD BE A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR IN A POSSIBLE PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THE PRD'S. THE STUDY WILL BEGIN THE LATTER PART OF DECEMBER AND WILL CONTINUE INTO THE FIRST QUARTER OF 2004.  EVEN THOUGH THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE THAT THE RESIDUE DISCOVERED AROUND THE PRD'S WAS DUE TO A PRODUCT RELEASE IN TRANSIT, CSXT IS SUBMITTING THIS REPORT IN ACCORDANCE WITH SECTION 171.16 OF THE US DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION HAZARDOUS MATERIALS REGULATIONS, 49 CFR.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1800 PDT ON THURSDAY, APRIL 17, 2003, A TANKER TRUCK OWNED BY FREDERICKSON TANK LINES OVERTURNED SHORTLY AFTER TURNING ONTO STATE ROAD 163, NEAR THE INTERSECTION OF US HIGHWAY 95 IN THE SOUTHERN PART OF CLARK COUNTY NEVADA.  THE VEHICLE'S TANKER HULL WAS RUPTURED AND APPROXIMATELY 3,500 GALLONS OF UNLEADED GASOLINE SPILLED ONTO UNDEVELOPED BARE GROUND. EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL VACUUMED UP MOST OF THE GASOLINE.  THE REMAINING CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND TRANSPORTED OFF-SITE FOR DISPOSAL (SEE ATTACHED WASTE DISPOSAL MANIFEST) UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF THE STATE ENVIRONMENTAL REGULATORY AGENCY AND THE STATE DOT (ED MILLERAN). THE AREA AFFECTED BY THE SPILL WAS BACKFILLED WITH CLEAN SOIL AND RESTORED TO ITS ORIGINAL CONDITION.  FREDERICKSON TANK LINES HAS SAFELY STORED THE DAMAGED TANKER AT THEIR LAS VEGAS, NV TERMINAL AND HAVE PROVIDED ADDITIONAL INSTRUCTIONS TO TANKER DRIVERS TO REDUCE THE RISK OF FUTURE ACCIDENTS.

column168: DRIVER WAS LOADING DIESEL FUEL AT A C&I CUSTOMER SITE.  PRIOR TO THE DELIVERY, THE DRIVER CHECKED THE ABOVEGROUND STORAGE TANK'S LEVEL GAUGE AND DETERMINED THAT THE ENTIRE LOAD WOULD FIT.  PRIOR TO UNLOADING HIS LAST COMPARTMENT, HE RE-CHECKED THE AST'S LEVEL GAUGE AND DETERMINED THE LAST COMPARTMENT WOULD FIT.  AS HE WAS UNLOADING HIS LAST COMPARTMENT THE AST'S HIGH LEVEL ALARM ACTIVATED.  ASSUMING THE ALARM WAS A NUISANCE ALARM (BECAUSE HE DETERMINED THE LOAD WOULD FIT) HE SILENCED THE ALARM, CONTINUED THE DELIVERY.  AT THE SAME TIME HE WENT TO SHUT THE TRUCK PUMP OFF, THE AST OVERFILLED.  IT WAS LATER DETERMINED THAT THE AST'S LEVEL GAUGE WAS INACCURATE.

column168: UPRR'S RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER NOTIFIED LANE A. SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY OF A REPORTED TANK CAR LEAKING AT 18TH STREET YARD IN KANSAS CITY, KS.  MR. SEKAVEC RESPONDED AND MET WITH MECHANICAL AND TRANSPORTATION PERSONNEL AND DETERMINED TANKCAR PLMX 135197 WAS SUSPECTED TO BE LEAKING.  MR. SEKAVEC ASSURED THE TRACK WAS PROPERLY LOCKED AND FLAGGED AND PROCEEDED TO THE CAR.  APPROACHING THE CAR, MR. SEKAVEC COULD HEAR A HISSING NOISE FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  AFTER CLIMBING THE CAR OPENED THE COVER ON THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING, MR. SEKAVEC DETERMINED THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM AT LEAST ONE VALVE.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT BOTH LIQUID VALVES AND THE VAPOR VALVE HAD PRODUCT OF VAPOR ESCAPING.  THE LIQUID VALVE HAD PRODUCT ESCAPING FROM AROUND THE PLUGS WHILE THE VAPOR VALVE HAD VAPOR ESCAPING FROM THE PACKAGING GLAND NUT ON THE OPERATING STEM.  THE VALVES WERE CHECKED AND DETERMINED TO BE AS TIGHT AS POSSIBLE WITH JUST HAND PRESSURE.  MR.  SEKAVEC USED AN 18" PIPE WRENCH TO FURTHER TIGHTEN THE VALVES IN AN ATTEMPT TO STOP ANY RELEASE OF MATERIAL.  THE A-END LIQUID VALVE AND VAPOR VALVE WERE BOTH TIGHTENED ENOUGH TO STOP THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  THE B-END VALVE, HOWEVER COULD NOT BE TIGHTENED SUFFICIENTLY TO STOP THE RELEASE.  THE PLUGS FOR BOTH LIQUID VALVES WERE TIGHTENED SECURELY AFTER THE VALVES WERE SHUT AS FAR AS POSSIBLE.  THE PACKAGING GLAND NUT WAS ALSO TIGHTENED ON THE VAPOR VALVE. TERRA NITROGEN (CAR LESSEE) WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE PROBLEMS WITH THE VALVES.  ALTERNATIVES FOR MOVING THE CAR WERE DISCUSSED WITH THEM AS WELL.  IT WAS DECIDED TO PURSUE OBTAINING A ONE-TIME MOVEMENT AUTHORITY TO GET THE CAR BACK TO WOODWARD, OK, WHERE REPAIRS OR REPLACEMENT OF THE VALVES WOULD TAKE PLACE.  MR. SEKAVEC APPLIED FOR AND RECEIVED A ONE-TIME MOVEMENT AUTHORITY (FRA-0304080) TO MOVE THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS CHECKED ON APRIL 7, 2003, PRIOR TO MOVEMENT AND NO FURTHER LEAKS WERE DETECTED FROM THIS CAR.  ALL THREE VALVES WERE TAGGED AS NEEDING REPAIRS PRIOR TO THE CAR BEING LOADED AGAIN.  NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS EXPECTED FROM THIS INCIDENT OTHER THAN THE MINOR RELEASE OF PRODUCT TO THE ATMOSPHERE PRIOR TO THE VALVES BEING SECURED.

WHILE PERFORMING RANDOM TANK CAR INSPECTIONS WITH THE KANSAS CITY, MO, FIRE DEPARTMENT, LANE A. SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY INSPECTED UTLX 202189.  DURING THE INSPECTION, MR. SEKAVEC DETECTED A HISSING SOUND IN THE AREA OF THE MANWAY COVER.  THE MANWAY WAS OPENED AND INVESTIGATION INDICATED THAT THE GASKET APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN DAMAGED AT SOME POINT IN THE PAST, CAUSING TWO DENTS OR DEPRESSED AREAS IN THE GASKET. AS A RESULT OF THESE DEPRESSIONS, THE CAR WAS LEAKING VAPOR.  THE GASKET WAS REMOVED FROM THE MANWAY COVER AND A TEMPORARY GASKET WAS FORMED FROM GORE-TEX SEALANT MATERIAL.  THE TEMPORARY GASKET WAS INSTALLED ON THE MANWAY NOZZLE AND THE COVER RESECURED.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION TO THE SHIPPER.  THE SHIPPER HAD BEEN CONTACTED BY UPRR'S RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER THROUGH CHEMTREC AND WAS ADVISED OF THE PROBLEM THAT WAS FOUND AS WELL AS THE SOLUTION.  THEY WERE ALSO ADVISED THAT THE GORE-TEX GASKET WAS ONLY FOR TEMPORARY REPAIRS AND THAT A NEW GASKET SHOULD BE INSTALLED WHEN THE CAR REACHES DESTINATION.

COMBINATION UNIT WAS IN ROUTE TO CONSIGNEE WHEN TRAILER SEPARATED FROM THE TRACTOR. UNIT WAS IN THE LEFT LANE OF NORTH BOUND SIDE OF I-69, TRAILER DROPPED ONTO THE SUPPORT LEGS AND TRAVELED FOR A CONSIDERABLE DISTANCE WHEN THE RIGHT SUPPORT APPARENTLY STARTED TO COLLAPSE AT WHICH TIME, THE UNIT VEERED TO THE RIGHT AND CROSSED THE RIGHT LANE COMING TO FINAL REST WITH THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER ON THE EMERGENCY LANE AND THE REAR IN THE RIGHT LANE NEAR MILE MARKER 14 BETWEEN THE EXIT AND ENTRANCE RAMPS TO THE INTERSTATE. THE LOCKING DEVICE ON THE TRACTOR 5TH WHEEL APPARENTLY FAILED TO HOLD SECURELY ALLOWING THE UNIT TO DISENGAGE FROM THE TRAILER. THE COUPLING DEVICE HAS BEEN EXAMINED BY THE MANUFACTURER (FONTAINE) AND THEY HAVE DETERMINED THAT THE LOCKING DEVICE WAS ONLY PARTIALLY ENGAGED. THE 5TH WHEEL HAS BEEN REPLACED ON THIS UNIT. CHEM-TREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THIS OCCURRENCE AS WERE NUMEROUS LOCAL/COUNTY/STATE AGENCIES NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER NOTIFIED AT 1115 HOURS 4-5-03, REPORT NUMBER 641385 TO MR NOWAK.

column168: A UNION PACIFIC CARMAN REPORTED THAT TANKCAR TCDX 11135 WAS LEAKING SULFURIC ACID AT A RATE OF A GALLON EVERY FIVE MINUTES IN SOUTH ST PAUL YARD. MIKE KOSCINSKI, SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CAR, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM AROUND A PLUG ON THE WASHOUT ON THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR. CORROSION HAD CAUSED THE PLUG TO NO LONGER SEAL THE WASHOUT HOLE. A COLLECTION TUB WAS PLACED UNDER THE CAR TO COLLECT DRIPPING ACID. SPECIAL AGENT KOSCINSKI WAS THEN CONFERRED WITH MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WHO INDICATED THAT THE CAR WOULD HAVE TO BE TRANSFERRED. HULCHER RESOURCES WAS CONTRACTED TO ASSIST WITH THE TRANSFER AND CLEANUP THE SPILLED ACID. THE TRANSFER TO TANKCAR PROX15002 WAS COMPLETED AT 2:30 PM ON SATURDAY, APRIL 12, 2003. CLEANUP OF APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF SPILLED ACID WAS ACCOMPLISHED BY EXCAVATING THREE 55 GALLON DRUMS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL. ADDITIONALLY, ANY RESIDUAL CONTAMINATION THAT REMAINED WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH A SODA ASH SLURRY. THE DRUMS OF WASTE WAS DISPOSED OF AS A HAZARDOUS WASTE.

column168: WHILE DOING TRAIN INSPECTIONS WITH PAM GINGERICH, FRA HAZMAT INSPECTOR, LANE A SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS MADE AWARE OF A TANK CAR (MWSX29627) WITH A BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE POSSIBLE OPEN. MR SEKAVEC PROCEEDED TO THE CAR AND DETERMINED THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HANDLE RETAINING PIN WAS NOT ABLE TO SECURE THE HANDLED. A DIFFERENT PIN WOULD NEED TO BE INSTALLED TO BE CORRECT. ALSO, THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS SLIGHTLY LOOSE AND WAS DRIPPING A VERY SMALL AMOUNT OF ALCOHOL ONTO THE GROUND. MR. SEKAVEC REMOVED THE CAP AND DETERMINED THAT WHILE THERE WAS A GASKET IN PLACE, IT HAD BEEN COMPRESSED TO THE EXTENT THAT IT WAS NOT SEALING PROPERLY AND WAS PREVENTING THE OUTLET CAP FROM BEING TIGHTENED COMPLETELY. MR. SEKAVEC REBENT THE HANDLE RETAINING PIN SO THAT IT WAS ABLE TO SECURE THE HANDLE AND STAY IN POSITION UNTIL THE CAR COULD BE SHOPPED FOR REPAIRS. HE ALSO FLIPPED THE GASKET OVER SO THAT A NEW SEALING SURFACE WOULD BE IN PLACE. THE OUTLET CAP WAS TIGHTENED AND THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION TO DESTINATION AND REPAIR. THE SHIPPER, MGP INGREDIENTS , WAS CONTACTED AND MR SEKAVEC MADE CONTACT WITH JOHN WOHLGEMUTH AND ADVISED HIM OF THE PROBLEM AND ITS RESOLUTION. MR.SEKAVEC ALSO ADVISED MR. WOLGEMUTH OF THE NECESSITY OF MAKING PROPER REPAIRS ON THE CAR PRIOR TO IT BEING LOADED AGAIN.

ON 04/05/2003 AT 0523 A LEAKING SHIPMENT WITH AN ODOR OF PERFUME WAS REPORTED IN BELLY 4 OF AIRCRAFT 818 AX, PARKED AT GATE BRAVO 72 OF OUR MAIN SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN KEVIN GAREN AND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR CHARLES JONES DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE.  THEY REMOVED THE  BOX FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THE BOX TO CONTAIN GLASS BOTTLES WITH PUMP SPRAY TYPE CLOSURES OF THE FOLLOWING VARIOUS PERFUMES: 1 X 5.94 ML OF "ENLIGHTNING", 1 X 100 ML OF "TSAR" AND 1 X 100 ML OF "BORA BORA".  THESE GLASS BOTTLES WERE WRAPPED IN PLASTIC AND PAPER.  THE CLOSURES ON THESE BOTTLES WERE NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS. THE BOTTLE OF "ENLIGHTNING" BROKE ALLOWING IT TO LEAK ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS OF 5.94 ML.  THE BACK OF THESE THREE BOTTLES STATED "FLAMMABLE".  THIS SHIPMENT ALSO CONTAINED 25 OTHER NON REGULATED PERFUMES.  THESE DID NOT LEAK.  THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, SEALED AND BAGGED THE SHIPMENT IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD IN THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED AND DID NOT HAVE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THERE WERE TWO EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR.  THEY WERE ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO THEIR WORK AREAS.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED.  NO FURTHER FOLLOW UP NEEDED.  CLEAR OF SCENE:  0548.  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE AT THE HAZ MAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

ICTF SECURITY REPORTED CONTAINER KNLU 325423, LEAKING IN YELLOW 314. INSPECTION NOTED THE CONTENTS TO BE PMX0110, A DOW CORNING COMMODITY.  THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE SECURED AND ISOLATED.  IT APPEARED THAT THE CONTENTS ONLY LEAKED WHEN THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED.  THE LADING CONSISTED OF 80 DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED, WITH BLOCKING AND BRACING NOT UP TO STANDARD FOR THE SECUREMENT OF HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES.  AS THE CONTENTS WERE NOT ACTIVELY LEAKING, AND THE CONTAINER WAS SECURED, IT WAS DECIDED TO WAIT UNTIL MONDAY TO TRANSFER THE CONTENTS.  UPON REMOVING AND INSPECTING THE DRUMS, TWO DRUMS WERE LOCATED FIVE ROWS IN FROM THE REAR DOORS, THAT WERE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM CHIMES.  THERE WAS NO VISIBLE DAMAGE TO THE CHIMES, AND IT APPEARS THE DRUMS WERE DEFECTIVE.  THE DRUMS WERE PATCHED AND PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT.  TWO ADDITIONAL DRUMS WERE LOCATED THAT SUSTAINED DAMAGE FROM LOAD SHIFT MOVEMENT SEVERE ENOUGH TO WARRANT THEM UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSIT.  THESE DRUMS WERE ALSO PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT.  THE CONTAINER WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE LADING PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. UPRR'S RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER NOTIFIED LANE A SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY OF A TANKCAR REPORTED TO BE LEAKING IN MARYSVILLE, KS.  MR SEKAVEC HAD RECEIVED A CALL FROM BILL CLARK, CAR FOREMAN, CONCERNING THIS CAR AS WELL.  GATX 20903 WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  MR SEKAVEC PROCEEDED TO MARYSVILLE AND SECURED THE CAR PRIOR TO BEGINNING HIS ASSESSMENT.  A CHECK OF THE PH OF THE RAINWATER COMING OFF OF THE CAR WAS MADE WITH NO APPRECIABLE CHANGE IN COLOR.  UPON CLIMBING THE CAR, MR SEKAVEC WAS ABLE TO DETERMINE THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISK HAD BURST,  APPARENTLY FROM A HYDRAULIC SURGE AT SOME POINT. THE DISK WAS REPLACED WITH A NEW DISK AND THE CAR RESECURED.  A CHECK OF THE RUN-OFF WATER AT THE TOP OF THE CAR SHOWED A MINOR COLOR CHANGE OF THE PH PAPER.  THE CAR WAS THEN SHAKEN TO VERIFY THE REPAIRS WERE MADE AND THE CAR WAS SECURED PROPERLY.  IT WAS THEN RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION TO DESTINATION.  THERE IS NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT EXPECTED FROM THIS INCIDENT AS ANY OF THE RESIDUAL ACID THAT MAY HAVE BEEN ON THE CAR WAS ALREADY WASHED AWAY BY THE RAIN THAT HAD BEEN AND WAS CONTINUING TO FALL.

HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR CHARLES JONES DOWNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL HE FOUND A FIBER BOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE. THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD IN THE HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. column168: AT 1155 HRS ON 4-9-03 WHILE CONDUCTING COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS, CTS MGR LERCH NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ON LOADED TANK CAR TILX 300736.  FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THE CAR TO GAUGE AT 140 PSI, WHICH INDICATED THAT THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE O-RINGS COULD BE DEFECTIVE. THE SHIPPER, PREMCO REFINING AND THE CONSIGNEE EXXON MOBIL, WERE BOTH CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE CONDITION OF THE CAR.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE THEN MADE BY EXXON MOBIL TO HAVE RESCAR MOBIL RAIL CAR REPAIR RESPOND.  THE O-RINGS WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE DRIED, PARTIALLY PINCHED, AND FLATTENED.  THE OLD O-RINGS WERE REPLACED WITH NEW VITON O-RINGS WHICH SECURED THE CAR FROM ANY FURTHER RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION AT 1520 HRS ON 4-14-03,  CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT A SWITCHMAN HAD REPORTED TANK TILX 300736 WAS AGAIN LEAKING.  THE CAR WAS LOCATED IN COADY YARD, TRACK #46. MGR LERCH INSPECTED THE TANK CAR AND NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE.  IMMEDIATE CHECK OF CAR PRESSURE REVEALED IT WAS APPROXIMATELY 280.0 PSI, AND GAUGED AT 7 INCHES OF OUTAGE, WHICH INDICATED THE CAR WAS OVER LOADED.  MGR LERCH RE CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, PREMCO REFINING WHO IN TURN MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE THE CAR PARTIALLY REDUCED. WITH THE USE OF HULCHER ENVIRONMENTAL AND ENTERPRISE TRANSPORTATION, APPROXIMATELY 9,475 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS OFF LOADED INTO A TANK TRUCK. AFTER OFF LOADING OF THE CAR, THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT STOPPED.  THE TANK CAR WAS THEN GAUGED AT 120 PSI WITH AN OUTAGE OF 37 INCHES.  IT WAS THEN RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  ARRANGEMENTS TO HANDLE THE PRODUCT IN THE TANK TRUCK WERE COORDINATED BETWEEN ENTERPRISE TRANSPORTATION AND PREMCO REFINING.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

column168: JAMES SMITH, BEAUMONT YARD MASTER HAD ADVISED THAT A CAR MAN HAD REPORTED A STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA COMING FROM TANK CARS UTLX 83695 AND UTLX 99001. CTS MANAGER FRANK LERCH WAS CONTACTED AND IMMEDIATE RESPONDED.  TANK CAR UTLX 99001 WAS FOUND WITH PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE "A" END LIQUID VALVE FLANGE AND FROM THE VAPOR VALVE PLUG.. ALL FOUR FLANGE NUTS ATTACHING THE VALVE TO THE PRESSURE PLATE WERE LOOSE AND THE VAPOR VALVE IN ITS CLOSED POSITION WAS FAULTY, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO LEAK.  AFTER TIGHTENING THE VAPOR VALVE PLUG APPROXIMATELY 3/4 OF A TURN AND TIGHTENING OF THE FOUR LIQUID VALVE FLANGE NUTS 1/2 TO 3/4 TURN EACH,  THE LEAKS STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS SECURED FROM ANY FURTHER RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  THE SHIPPER, NECHES INDUSTRIAL PARK, BILL CASTLEMAN FACILITY MANAGER WAS CONTACTED, AND RESPONDED TO THE SITE.  THE EXCEPTIONS WERE EXPLAINED TO MR CASTLEMAN, AND BECAUSE OF THE POOR CONDITION OF THE CAR, ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO OFF LOAD AND HOME SHOP IT FOR NECESSARY REPAIRS.  TANK CAR UTLX 83695 WAS NOTED WITH NO EXCEPTIONS, AND ALLOWED TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS IMPACTED, OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

ICTF SECURITY REPORTED CONTAINER KNLU 335704 LEAKING, FIVE TO SIX DRIPS PER SECOND ONTO THE PAVEMENT.  THE PRODUCT WAS POOLING WITH LESS THAN ONE GALLON, BELOW THE REAR DOORS OF THE CONTAINER, LOCATED IN E5, SLOT 280. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD ISOLATED AND CONTAINED PRIOR TO INSPECTION.  UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS DEVELOPED THE LADING CONSISTED OF 80 DRUM, DOUBLE STACKED.  THE BLOCKING AND BRACING WAS SUBSTANDARD, WHICH CONTRIBUTED TO THE LOAD SHIFTING.  THE USE OF HIGHWAY GLUE CHOCKS TO SUPPORT THE HORIZONTAL 2X6 LUMBER AT THE REAR DOOR IS NOT A RECOMMENDED PRACTICE, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD PER THE AAR BOE PAMPHLET 6C FOR THE SECUREMENT OF HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES TRANSPORTED VIA RAIL.  WHILE REMOVING THE DRUMS, IT WAS NOTED THE SHIPPER USED NARROW CUT STRIPS OF PLYWOOD FOR THE BILEVEL SEPARATION.  DURING TRANSPORTATION, THE DRUMS SHIFTED AND ROTATED, AND THE NARROW STRIPS OF PLYWOOD MOVED, CREATING AN EVEN LARGER UNEVEN SURFACE FOR THE DRUMS TO REST UPON.  ONCE THE PLYWOOD SHIFTED FORWARD OR AFT, LESS THAN HALF OF THE BOTTOM HEAD OF THE DRUM RESTED ON THE PLYWOOD SURFACE.  IN MOST CASES, THE ROWS OF DRUMS TILTED TO WHERE THE TILTED DRUM HEADS WERE RESTING TWO INCHES BELOW THE ADJACENT ROW OF DRUMS.  AS THE DRUMS SPUN IN PLACE, THEY THINNED THE METAL OF THE ADJACENT DRUMS.  TWO DRUMS WERE FOUND LEAKING FROM DAMAGE TO THE BOTTOM CHIMES FROM ADJACENT DRUMS.  ESTIMATED TOTAL PRODUCT LOST FROM THE TWO DAMAGED DRUMS WAS 40 GALLONS WHILE IN TRANSIT.  A MAJORITY OF THE REMAINING DRUMS SUSTAINED SUFFICIENT DAMAGE TO WARRANT THEM UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSPORTATION.  THE LEAKING DRUMS WERE PATCHED AND PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR CONTAINMENT.  THE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE ALSO PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER PER THEIR REQUEST.  THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE AND RELEASED EMPTY TO THE VESSEL OPERATOR.

column168: THE CTL DRIVER STAGED THE UNIT AT THE CUSTOMERS OFF-LOADING SITE AND PROCEEDED TO TAKE A SAMPLE OF THE PRODUCT FOR THE CUSTOMER.  THE CTL DRIVER THEN STARTED TO COMPLETE HIS HOOK-UP AT THE TRAILER AND THE CUSTOMER'S CONNECTION.  THE DRIVER STARTED TO PUT PRESSURE ON THE CARGO TANK TO OFF-LOAD THE PRODUCT WHEN THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT A SMALL LEAK HAD DEVELOPED.  THE DRIVER THEN SHUT THE PROCESS DOWN AND TRIED TO STOP THE LEAK WHEN SOME OF THE PRODUCT HAD SPRAYED ON THE DRIVER.  HE IMMEDIATELY WENT TO THE SAFETY SHOWER TO WASH OFF THE AFFECTED AREA.  THE DRIVER THEN NOTIFIED THE PLANT PERSONNEL THAT HE HAD SPRAYED SOME OF THE PRODUCT ON HIMSELF.  AT THIS TIME THE DRIVER AND 2 PLANT EMPLOYEES WENT BACK TO THE UNIT AND HAD NOTICED THAT THE LEAK HAD STOPPED AND THEY PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE DISCHARGE BY THE TRAILER.  THEN THE DRIVER MADE ANOTHER ATTEMPT TO REPAIR THE LEAK AND AT THIS TIME THE CONNECTION CAME LOOSE AND SOME OF THE PRODUCT HAD BEEN RELEASED AND AT THIS TIME THE DRIVER AND THE 2 PLANT EMPLOYEES HAD BEEN EXPOSED TO THE PRODUCT.  FIRST AID TREATMENT WAS GIVEN TO ALL PERSON AFFECTED BY THE PRODUCT.  THE 2 PLANT EMPLOYEES HAD VERY MINOR EXPOSURE AND ONLY RECEIVED FIRST AID TREATMENT BY THE PLANT FACILITY AND RECEIVE NO FURTHER TREATMENT.  THE DRIVER FOR CTL WAS ALSO GIVEN FIRST AID TREATMENT BY THE PLANT FACILITY FOR HIS MINOR EXPOSURE.  CTL INSTRUCTED THEIR EMPLOYEE TO BE CHECK OUT AT A NEAR BY CLINIC DUE TO PRECAUTIONARY REASONS.  THE DRIVER WAS RELEASED BACK TO FULL DUTY AND DID NOT LOSE ANY TIME.  A CALL WAS MADE THE FOLLOWING DAY TO CHECK ON THE PLANT EMPLOYEES MEDICAL CONDITION.  IT WAS STATED TO CTL BY A MR. DANIELS THAT NO FURTHER PROBLEMS AND THAT THE 2 EMPLOYEES WERE FINE.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH AND PH STRIPE WERE USE TO TEST THE NEUTRALIZED PRODUCT.  PLANT PERSONNEL CLEANED UP THE NEUTRALIZED PRODUCT. THE CTL DRIVER WAS EVALUATED BY THE TERMINAL MANAGER AND A CERTIFIED DRIVER TRAINER AND A DECISION WAS MADE TO RE-TRAIN THE DRIVER FOR A PERIOD OF 1 WEEK AND ANOTHER EVALUATION WAS COMPLETED PRIOR TO HIS RELEASE TO OPERATE AS A SOLO DRIVER.  THE DRIVER WAS RE-TRAINED ON PROPER OFF-LOADING PROCEDURES AND EMERGENCY SHUT PROCEDURE.  THE DRIVER WAS ALSO GIVEN INSTRUCTION ON PROPER CONTROL MEASURE TO PROTECT THE PERSONNEL AROUND THE AFFECTED AREA FROM BEING EXPOSED TO HAZARDOUS SITUATIONS.

column168: AT 1600 HRS ON 4-10-03, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED BY THE RMCC THAT MIKE ROGERS MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS HAD REPORTED TANK CAR DUPX 29218 TO BE LEAKING.  THE TANK CAR WAS LOCATED ON THE NORTH END OF TRACK 310, ENGLEWOOD YARD;  HOUSTON, TX.  IN COMPANY OF REGIONAL MGR, TIM OBRIEN, LERCH INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND PRODUCT LEAKING DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR AND EVAPORATING AS IT CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE ATMOSPHERE.  THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE WAS FROM THE LIQUID BALL VALVE WHICH WAS 1/3 TURN OPEN.  IT WAS ALSO NOTED THAT THE LIQUID VALVE PLUG WAS IN POSITION, BUT WAS NOT WRENCH TIGHT.  THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE VALVE PLUG TIGHTENED APPROXIMATELY 2 TURNS.  THE LEAK STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS SECURE FOR TRANSPORTATION.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED, OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.  CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THE SHIPPER, DUPONT VIA CHEM-TREC, AND TOM KEEFER, EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM LEADER WAS ADVISED OF THE NOTED EXCEPTIONS.  HE INDICATED THAT HE WOULD CONTACTED PERSONNEL AT THE LA PORTE, TX., PLANT WERE THE CAR WAS LOADED AND HAVE THEM REVIEW SECUREMENT PROCEDURES.

THE FREIGHT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER.  THE BAG WAS LOADED ON TOP OF A LOAD RACK AND WAS NOT PROPERLY PROTECTED WITH PLYWOOD DUNNAGE AND WAS DAMAGED BY THE SKID THAT WAS LOADED NEXT TO IT IN TRANSIT.  THE PRODUCT WAS PROPERLY RECOUPED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND WILL BE PICKED UP FOR DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WILL BE RETRAINED ON THE PROPER USE OF DUNNAGE AROUND BAGS.

RESCAR REPLACED THE O-RINGS AND THE MANWAY COVER GASKET. THE CAR WAS DETERMINED TO BE SECURED AND WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER FOR CTL (CLYDE HILTON) WAS WESTBOUND ON HIGHWAY 62 IN MONTEREY TN APPROACHING A RIGHT HAND CURVE WITH A REDUCE SPEED FOR THE CURVE.  THE SPEED LIMIT IS 55 MPH BEFORE THE CURVE AND THE SPEED PRIOR TO ENTERING THE CURVE IS REDUCED TO 25 MPH.  MR. HILTON DOES NOT REMEMBER THE EXACT SPEED IN WHICH HE WAS TRAVELING AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT.  AN ESTIMATED SPEED WAS APPROXIMATELY 30-35 MPH AS HE ATTEMPTED TO NEGOTIATE THE TURN.  AS THE CTL UNIT WAS ABOUT HALFWAY THROUGH THE TURN THE UNIT OVERTURNED ONTO ITS LEFT SIDE KNOCKING DOWN SEVERAL GUARD RAILS BEFORE GOING OVER THE EMBANKMENT.  THE UNIT CAME TO REST UP AGAINST SEVERAL TREES THAT PREVENTED THE UNIT FROM DESCENDING ALL THE WAY DOWN THE EMBANKMENT.  THE FIRST CALL CAME INTO CTL FROM TYLER SMITH WHO HAD ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 7:15 AM EASTERN TIME.  JEFF PARKER FROM CTL RECEIVED THE CALL AND PROCEEDED TO GET THE INITIAL INFORMATION IN ORDER TO GET THE PROPER PERSONNEL IN PLACE TO HANDLE THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  JEFF PARKER IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES TO ASSIST IN MANAGING AND CONTACTING FERGUSON HARBOUR TO RESPOND TO THE ACCIDENT SITE.  THE LOADED TANKER WAS ON ITS SIDE AND A SMALL LEAK HAD DEVELOPED AROUND THE DOME LID AREA.  INITIALLY ATTEMPTS WERE MADE BY THE FIRST RESPONDERS TO STOP THE LEAK THAT HAD DEVELOPED.  THE WAS MINIMIZED BY THE FIRST RESPONDERS, BUT WAS NOT COMPLETELY STOPPED.  WHEN FERGUSON HARBOUR ARRIVED ON SITE, ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO BETTER SECURE THE LEAK AND THEIR ATTEMPTS TO USE MATERIAL TO PLUG THE LEAK FAILED.  POLY SHEETING WAS PLACED DOWN AROUND THE AREA TO CAPTURE THE LEAKING PRODUCT THAT WAS THEN FUNNELED INTO A BUCKET.  MR. HILTON WAS TRANSPORTED BY AMBULANCE TO CUMBERLAND MEDICAL CENTER IN COOKEVILLE, TN.  MR. HILTON WAS TREATED FOR A BROKEN WRIST AND SOME MINOR CUTS.  MR. HILTON NEVER CAME IN CONTACT WITH ANY OF THE PRODUCT THAT WAS RELEASED IN THE OVER TURN ACCIDENT.  MR. HILTON WAS RELEASED FROM THE CUMBERLAND MEDICAL CENTER AROUND 11:30 AM ON THE SAME DAY OF THE ACCIDENT.  CTL'S INSURANCE ADJUSTER WAS SENT TO THE CUMBERLAND MEDICAL CENTER TO PICK UP MR. HILTON AT TAKE HIM TO A MOTEL UNTIL FLIGHT ARRANGEMENT COULD BE MADE.  FLIGHT ARRANGEMENT WERE MADE FOR MR. HILTON TO FLY OUT OF THE NASHVILLE AIRPORT THE NEXT DAY.  CTL ARRANGED FOR ANOTHER TANKER TO BE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT TO ASSIST FERGUSON HARBOUR IN TRANSFER OF THE PRODUCT.  THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED AND THE OVER TURN TANKER WAS UP RIGHT AND REMOVED FROM THE SCENE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  FERGUSON HARBOUR PREPARED THE SITE FOR THE CLEAN UP WORK OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  EXCAVATION OF THE ACCIDENT SITE BEGAN THE NEXT DAY.  FERGUSON HARBOUR HANDLED THE DISPOSAL OF THE CONTAMINATED SOIL. PLEASE SEE ATTACHED DISPOSAL MANIFEST.

THE CLOSURES ON THESE BOTTLES WERE NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS.  SIX OF THESE BOTTLES WERE BROKEN LEAKING APPROXIMATELY 79.8 ML. HE REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, SEALED AND BAGGED THE SHIPMENT IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD IN THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED AND DID NOT HAVE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR.  HE WAS ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO HIS WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED. NO FURTHER FOLLOW UP NEEDED. column168: FILE 2307 F & D SHIPPER: GLAZURA AWB# PRG 3201169435 PNO.  ONE 04/26/2003 AT 0220 A SHIPMENT WITH A CHEMICAL ODOR WAS REPORTED AT DOOR "B" 14 OF OUR MAIN SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO, 45177.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS TIMOTHY HINES AND GREG GRAGG DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND AN INTERNATIONAL PLASTIC EXPRESS BAG WITH NO VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE.  THEY REMOVED THE BOX FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THE BOX TO CONTAIN 16 FIBERBOARD BOXES, TWO WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE.  THESE 16 BOXES CONTAINED GLASS BOTTLES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES WHICH CONTAINED THE FOLLOWING LIQUIDS: 6 X 500 @ G OF "TRICHLOROETHYLENE", 59 X 100 G OF "TURPENTINE", 1 X 500 G OF "CYCLOHEXANOL", 1 X 500 G OF "PBO U306, TURPENTINE, CYCLOHEXANONE" AND 4 X 25 G OF "LSP 92828".  THESE GLASS BOTTLES WERE SECURED IN STYROFOAM PACKAGING INSIDE THEIR FIBERBOARD BOXES. THE CLOSURES ON THESE BOTTLES WERE NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS.  THE CLOSURE ON ONE OF THE 500 G BOTTLES OF "TRICHLOROETHYLENE" CANE LOOSE ALLOWING THE BOTTLE TO LEAK APPROXIMATELY 25 ML OF ITS CONTENTS.  THE CLOSURE ON ONE OF THE 20 G BOTTLES OF "L&P 92828" CAME LOOSE ALLOWING THE BOTTLE TO LEAK ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS.  THE LIQUIDS LEAKING FROM THESE BOTTLES WERE CONTAINED INSIDE OF THE INTERNATIONAL PLASTIC EXPRESS BAG.  THEY REPLACED THE ITEM BACK INTO BOXES, SEALED AND BAGGED THE SHIPMENT IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IN INTO A RECOVERY DRUM. THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD IN THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED AND DID NOT HAVE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THERE WERE TWO EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR.  THEY WERE ADVISED WHAT THE ODOR WAS AND RETURNED TO THEIR WORK AREAS.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED.  NO FURTHER FOLLOW UP NEEDED.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 0306 THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE AT THE HAZ MAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

column168: AT 1220HRS ON 4-21-03, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT MR. SHIRLEY, SETTEGAST YARDMASTER, REPORTED TANK CAR RTSX 23007 TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR.  THE TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED IN THE MIDDLE OF TRACK 404, SETTEGAST YARD.  UPON BEING NOTIFIED, MGR LERCH REQUESTED SHIPPER NOTIFICATION VIA CHEMTREC.  INSPECTION OF CAR IN COMPANY OF REGIONAL CTS MGR. TIMOTHY O'BRIEN, DETERMINED CAR WAS A THREE COMPARTMENT RAILCAR.  PRODUCT WAS OBSERVED TO BE DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP ON COMPARTMENT ONE AT A RATE OF APPROXIMATELY 12 OUNCES AN HOUR.  CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP TO BE LOOSE 1/4 TURN, AND THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS NOTED TO BE OPEN FOUR TURNS.  ADDITIONALLY, EIGHT OF EIGHT MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE FOUND TO BE IN POSITION, BUT NOT WRENCH TIGHT.  ADDITIONAL EXCEPTIONS NOTED ON THE CARE ARE AS FOLLOWS.  BOTH COMPARTMENT TWO AND THREE HAD EIGHT OF EIGHT OF EIGHT MANWAY SWING BOLTS IN POSITION, BUT NOT WRENCH TIGHT.BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED WITH NO SIGNS OF LEAKAGE.  THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVES ON COMPARTMENTS TWO AND THREE WERE ALSO FOUND TO BE OPEN APPROXIMATELY ONE TURN EACH.  ON COMPARTMENT THREE, THE LIQUID VALVE PLUG WAS FOUND TO BE HANGING FROM THE SAFETY CHAIN AND NOT SECURED ONTO THE VALVE.  THE PLUG WAS SECURED INTO THE VALVE WITH ALL OTHER NOTED EXCEPTIONS CORRECTED.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE. THERE WAS NO CLEAN-UP RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE, AS THE PRODUCT EVAPORATED UPON CONTACT WITH THE ATMOSPHERE.  THE SHIPPER LOS ANGELES CHEMICAL WAS CONTACTED AND CHRIS JOHNSON, VICE PRESIDENT OF OPERATIONS WAS ADVISED OF THE EXCEPTIONS FOUND.

column168: TWO(2) 1,000 GALLON ANHYDROUS AMMONIA NURSE TANKS WERE BEING TOWED BY A PICKUP TRUCK ON GREENE COUNTY HAD SURFACED ROAD P-46. OTHERWISE, 4 MILES N. OF 120 ST. ON "X" AVENUE, WHICH IS THE 911 ADDRESS. THE DRIVER OF THE PICKUP TRUCK PULLED TO THE LEFT WHEN MEETING A CAR AND THE NURSE TANKS DROPPED OFF THE PAVEMENT AND BEGAN SWERVING WHICH ENDED UP WITH THE TANKS IN THE W. DITCH WITH THE FIRST TANK ON ITS SIDE AND NOT LEAKING. THE SECOND TANK WENT END OVER END, BUSTED THE ROLL CAGE OFF AND THE BUSTED OFF THE LIQUID WITHDRAWAL VALVE CAUSING THE AMMONIA LEAK. THE REMAINDER OF THIS REPORT IS FORMATTED TO ADDRESS THE REQUIREMENTS OF SUBRULE 567-131.1(2) OF THE IOWA ADMINISTRATIVE CODE: A) THE EXACT LOCATION OF THE HAZARD CONDITION: FOUR TENTHS OF A MILE N. OF 120TH STREET ON "X" AVENUE ON GREENE COUNTY HARD SURFACE ROAD P-46. THIS LOCATION IS APPROXIMATELY 4 1/2 MILE SOUTH OF HARCOURT, IA. B) THE EXACT TIME AND DATE OR DISCOVERY OF HAZARDOUS CONDITION: THE DRIVER OF THE PICKUP TRUCK USED HIS CELL PHONE TO CALL THE FC LOCATION AT PATON, WHICH IS CLOSER TO THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 1:40 PM ON APRIL 2, 2003. C) THE NAME OF THE MATERIAL, THE MANUFACTURE'S NAME, AND THE VOLUME OF EACH MATERIAL INVOLVED IN THE HAZARD CONDITION IN ADDITION TO CONTAMINANTS WITHIN THE MATERIAL WITHIN THE MATERIAL IF THEY, BY THEMSELVES, COULD CAUSE A HAZARD CONDITION: THE MATERIAL RELEASED WAS AGRICULTURAL NITROGEN FERTILIZER IN THE FORM OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA (NH3). APPROXIMATELY 850 GALLONS OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAS RELEASED. MANUFACTURER OF THE RELEASED AMMONIA CAN NOT BE DETERMINED.

NRC#643031 GREAT LAKES CHEMICAL LEASES A TANK CAR FROM UTLX (UTLX 42403) FOR ON-SITE STORAGE OF ETHYL BROMIDE.  THIS CAR IS NOT SHIPPED TO CUSTOMERS, BUT FILLED AND TRANSLOADED AT THIS GLCC FACILITY.  AFTER LOADING THE CAR, A DRIP WAS DISCOVERED AT THE BOTTOM CENTER PORTION OF THE CAR. THERE ARE NO BOTTOM OUTLETS ON THIS CAR, SO IT IS ASSUMED THAT POSSIBLY THE SHELL WAS LEAKING.  THE CAR WAS UNLOADED, CLEANED AND PURGED AND SENT TO UTLX FOR IDENTIFICATION OF THE LEAK AND TO REPAIR IT.  WE WILL REQUEST CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT POSSIBLE REOCCURRENCE.  WE EXPECT THIS INFORMATION IN THE DISTANT FUTURE.
